Aim:

Simulation of Supermarket System

Theory:

A supermarket system consists of customers arriving at billing counters to complete purchases. 
Customers wait in a queue if the billing counter is busy and receive service once the counter becomes available.

This simulation helps analyze:

Customer waiting time
Queue length
Billing counter utilization
Customer flow efficiency

The system follows a single-server queueing model where one billing counter serves customers sequentially.

COMMANDS:
GENERATE
Creates customer arrivals at specified intervals.
QUEUE
Places customers into the waiting line.
SEIZE
Allocates the billing counter to a customer.
DEPART
Removes customers from the queue after service begins.
ADVANCE
Simulates billing and exit processing time.
RELEASE
Frees the billing counter after service completion.
TERMINATE
Removes the customer from the system or stops simulation.
EQU
Defines the billing counter facility.
Scenario Overview:

The supermarket system contains:

One billing counter
One billing queue
Continuous customer arrivals

Customers arrive every 6 minutes, wait in the billing queue if necessary, complete billing, and then exit the supermarket.

Key Components:
1. Customers

Customers arrive randomly for billing service.

2. Billing Counter

Processes customer billing one at a time.

3. Queue

Customers wait in the billing queue if the counter is busy.

4. Exit Process

Customers leave the supermarket after billing is completed.

Small Conclusion Template

The GPSS simulation represents a supermarket billing system with a single billing counter and one queue.
Customers were processed sequentially through the billing system. The simulation helps analyze customer 
waiting time, queue behavior, and billing counter utilization for efficient supermarket operations.
